How about this answer?

### Modification points:
- In your script, the function of `onOpen()` which is used as a simple trigger is been putting in a function of `OrderByEvent()`. By this, when the Spreadsheet is opened, `onOpen()` is not run. Even when `OrderByEvent()` is installed as the installable trigger, when `OrderByEvent()` is run, `onOpen()` is not run.
	- By this, the script for sorting is not run.
- When the OnOpen event trigger is used, you can use the event object.
	- For example, `SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSheet()` can be modified to `event.source` in your script. Of course, `event.source.getActiveSheet()` can be used.
	- When event object is used, the process cost can be reduced. [Ref](https://gist.github.com/tanaikech/4892c97df7ac0504ffd715c2dd6cd546)

When above points are reflected to your script, it becomes as follows. Please think of this as just one of several answers.

### Modified script:
	function autoSort(sheet) {
	  var SORT_COLUMN_INDEX = 10;
	  var ASCENDING = true;
	  var NUMBER_OF_HEADER_ROWS = 1;
	  var range = sheet.getDataRange();
	  if (NUMBER_OF_HEADER_ROWS &gt; 0) {
	    range = range.offset(NUMBER_OF_HEADER_ROWS, 0);
	  }
	  range.sort( {
	    column: SORT_COLUMN_INDEX,
	    ascending: ASCENDING
	  } );
	}

	function onOpen(event) {
	  autoSort(event.source);
	}

- In your script, the script can work using the simple trigger. So in this case, it is not required to install the installable trigger. `onOpen()` is automatically run and works when the Spreadsheet is opened.

### Note:
- In this modification, it supposes that your sort script works.

### References:
- [Simple Triggers](https://developers.google.com/apps-script/guides/triggers/)
- [Event Objects](https://developers.google.com/apps-script/guides/triggers/events)
- [Benchmark: Event Objects for Google Apps Script](https://gist.github.com/tanaikech/4892c97df7ac0504ffd715c2dd6cd546)

